						<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#330000" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												<DIV>Tremelo, I think you nailed the state of the bard and the state of EQ perfectly.&nbsp; I wish I could 5-star that post; I think it's the single best one I've ever seen on the EQLive boards.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>In the MPG groups I've been in, we're lucky if we can handle 1 add.&nbsp; If we get 2, the game is up, and we are screwed.&nbsp; If I get a freeze frame on a pull, I'm dead.&nbsp; A single series of hits flattens me.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>My own take is a bit different.&nbsp; I have done just about everything with my bard that I wanted to do.&nbsp; Aside from my guild, there isn't much to make me want to keep playing Feroce.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>After I hit 67, I stopped levelling my bard.&nbsp; I just didn't see the point.&nbsp; I don't play a bard to watch my hitpoints increase half a percent now and then, or to get an upgrade to a song that was already working fine.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Here's my magelo:</DIV>
<DIV><A href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=601903" target=_blank>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=601903</A></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>If you look at my magelo, you'll see a character with TONS of bells and whistles.&nbsp; Clickies.&nbsp; Worn effects.&nbsp; Illusions.&nbsp; Spunky weapons.&nbsp; An orb that MGB summons bread.&nbsp; It used to be that uber equipment wasn't all about the stats (though that has always been a factor).&nbsp; It used to be about what new things you could do that you couldn't do before.&nbsp; It was about new tactics you could try, new ways you could turn heads, and new effects that gave your character an edge.&nbsp; Sometimes, when the devs put in new effects and items, things got unbalanced, and we'd get upset, and it would get fixed.&nbsp; Manastones, rubicite armor, they all got fixed properly.&nbsp; The important thing was, the developers were creative, and they were willing to take risks to keep things interesting.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I'm talking about items like the mana robe, like the fungi tunic, like the lute of the howler, like the Goblin Gazuli Ring.&nbsp; I'm talking about items that people look at, and say "**SMURF**?"&nbsp; I'm talking about items like the Kobold Jester Crown, with tons of CHA, but negative INT.&nbsp;&nbsp;These items were made for a&nbsp;purpose, and not just to be your next piece of uberriffic gear.&nbsp; Each had some very specific advantages, and some very specific drawbacks.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Today's uber gear has no drawbacks.&nbsp; It is simply a linear progression of what endgame gear was in the previous expansion.&nbsp; Today's top-level spells and songs are the same as yesterday's, with a marginally higher number.&nbsp; Today's new AA's bring nothing new, they just bump up the old a little bit more, to give us something to work for.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think that sony is a victim of success.&nbsp; The OOW expansion, from a design standpoint, takes no risks.&nbsp; That is its major flaw.&nbsp; There are no new concepts in this expansion.&nbsp; There are no new gameplay features to speak of.&nbsp; Back in the day, Kunark doubled the size of the world, added a new, interesting race, and a LOT of content for higher-level characters to go after.&nbsp; Velious brought about the formation of the true raiding guild, with a lot of content designed for a lot of people.&nbsp; Luclin brought in the bazaar, and the spire teleport system.&nbsp; PoP took raiding to new heights, brought about FAST world travel, and opened up the higher levels to the more casual players.&nbsp; Ykesha brought in a host of new play features.&nbsp; LDoN helped people learn how to group and dungeon crawl properly.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Since then, we have GoD, and OOW.&nbsp; GoD introduced the tradeskill ship-city in Abysmal Sea, and that's about it.&nbsp; Everything else was visually interesting, but boring after you saw it the first time.&nbsp; Likewise, in OOW, there wasn't anything new and exciting in the game, just recycled ideas and bigger numbers behind the mobs and the gear.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Until these last two expansions, there were always some new interesting design ideas to be explored with each release.&nbsp; Sony has done a great job of class balancing.&nbsp; In doing so, the game has become stale.&nbsp; I would rather see the developers come up with some fresh, UN-balancing ideas.&nbsp; Expansions should be for fun, new stuff.&nbsp; They can always fix stuff in patches.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
																																		<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
														<p>Impressario Feroce of <br>Molto Espressivo, the All-Bard Guild on<br>Firiona Vie
